ce:section.ce:para:
Some preliminary experiments were conducted to evaluate the PEC performance of the CQDs/WO3 photoanodes in 1 M H2SO4 solution under back side illumination. Fig. S7 illustrates the LSV curves of WO3 and various CQDs/WO3 electrodes. It was found that the optimal photocurrent density was obtained for the WO3 electrode with 1.93 wt% of CQDs (Fig. S7
                     ). The WO3 electrode with 1.93 wt% of CQDs was selected in the following experiments. Fig. 5
                     a shows the LSV curves of WO3 and 1.93%CQDs/WO3 electrodes. Both of the samples show negligible dark current densities. Upon illumination, the pristine WO3 electrode shows a photocurrent density of 0.65 mA cm−2 at 1.0 V vs. Ag/AgCl (∼1.23 V vs. RHE). This result is comparable to the previously reported values for the bare WO3 photoanode [17]. However, the 1.93%CQDs/WO3 electrode achieves a current of 1.46 mA cm−2 at the same potential. IPCE was measured to evaluate the PEC activity of WO3 before and after the modification of CQDs (Fig. 5b). As can be seen, an enhanced UV and visible photoelectric response could be obtained for 1.93%CQDs/WO3. The IPCE values of 1.93%CQDs/WO3 show obvious improvements in the short wavelength region, which may be attributed to the efficient interfacial charge transfer induced by CQDs. Furthermore, in wavelength region above 480 nm in the magnified plots (the inset in Fig. 5b), the pristine WO3 showed negligible IPCE value due to its intrinsic limitation of absorption ability in accordance with its optical band gap of 2.6 eV. While the 1.93%CQDs/WO3 composite showed apparent IPCE promotions in the visible light region. Fig. S8 presents the integrated photocurrent densities based on the IPCE data for the WO3 and the 1.93%CQDs/WO3 electrodes. The pristine WO3 electrode showed no obvious change of the integrated photocurrent density in the wavelength region 450–600 nm, while an improved photocurrent density of 0.27 mA cm−2 was observed for the 1.93%CQDs/WO3 electrode, indicating that CQDs may act as a semiconductor [37]. In addition, the 1.93%CQDs/WO3 electrode exhibited an increased photocurrent density of (0.81 mA cm−2) as compared with the pristine WO3 electrode at 1.0 V vs. Ag/AgCl in Fig. 5a, which was much higher than that (0.27 mA cm−2) caused by the semi-conducting property of CQDs, indicating that some other reasons may be associated with the improved PEC performance of the 1.93%CQDs/WO3 electrode.
